---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import { projects } from "../../data/research";
import { approach, criteria, foundation, identityLong, questions } from "../../data/program";

// The research page, in the order a reader needs it:
//   the program → the current case → the linguistic hypothesis (+ criteria)
//   → the developmental question → the LM question → methods & existing work.
//
// It must stay honest about status, which means keeping these distinct:
//   - a current theoretical question (being worked out),
//   - an exploratory LM pilot (built, smoke-test only),
//   - a developmental component (being scoped — NOT a running experiment, no
//     collaborator or institution named),
//   - completed methodological work (the collaborations).
//
// Do NOT reintroduce: "human arm" / "LM arm", "one theory two systems", or any
// claim that internal geometry adjudicates Kratzer vs. Lassiter. Positioning
// copy comes from data/program.ts. See CONTEXT.md for the red lines.
const modus = projects.find((p) => p.href === "/research/modus");

const collaborations = [
  {
    name: "Latent Control States",
    org: "DFKI",
    text: "Does prompt framing shift a causally relevant latent state, or only the output? My contribution: a utilitarian minimal-pair probe — dilemma × benefit-size × framing — testing whether the choice tracks the real stakes or only surface pressure. Where the interpretability technique came from.",
  },
  {
    name: "Cross-lingual ProtoBias",
    org: "an established NLP group",
    text: "Does a vision-language model track meaning, or language- and culture-specific prototype shortcuts? My contribution: the cross-lingual behavioural evaluation across seven languages that extends the group's forthcoming paper.",
    href: "https://github.com/xchuan-li/cross_lingual_protobias",
    hrefLabel: "GitHub ↗",
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Research · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="Experimental and computational semantics: whether epistemic possibility expressions merely weaken commitment, or also keep content-specific alternatives available for subsequent evidence updating — and how that question becomes testable for cognitive science and language models."
>
  <h1 class="text-2xl font-medium tracking-tight mb-2">Research</h1>
  <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mb-4 max-w-prose">
    {identityLong} The work is one program rather than a list of projects, and it runs in one
    direction: <strong>{approach.charAt(0).toLowerCase() + approach.slice(1)}</strong> How that works
    in general is on the <a href="/approach" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:opacity-75">approach page</a>.
    This page is the current case.
  </p>

  <!-- ============ CURRENT CASE ============ -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <p class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Current case
    </p>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-medium tracking-tight mb-3">Epistemic modality</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose mb-3">
      Someone says <em>“It might be a star.”</em> Does that expression merely signal uncertainty — or
      does it also help maintain <em>the star</em> as a live alternative for subsequent reasoning?
      {foundation}
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose">
      The semantics literature has analysed <em>might</em> in terms of alternatives and keeping
      possibilities open. Developmental work has studied nonverbal modal reasoning, and separately the
      acquisition of modal language. Recent work suggests language models are sensitive to epistemic
      language but inconsistent in modal reasoning. What I have not found is a study that holds the
      available information constant and asks whether linguistic modality selectively maintains a
      <em>particular</em> alternative.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ THE HYPOTHESIS ============ -->
  <section class="mt-11">
    <p class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      The linguistic hypothesis
    </p>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-medium tracking-tight mb-3">What would make this a real effect</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose mb-4">
      "Keeping an alternative available" is too easy to satisfy as stated: mentioning the
      proposition, priming on the modal word, finding the sentence memorable, being generally
      unsure, or fixating on a first answer would all produce something that looks like it. So the
      effect has to be pinned down in advance. A genuine alternative-maintenance effect should be:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-none p-0 m-0 mb-4 border-t border-[var(--color-border)] max-w-prose">
      {criteria.map((c) => (
        <li class="flex items-baseline gap-2 flex-wrap py-2.5 border-b border-[var(--color-border)] text-sm">
          <span class="font-mono text-[11.5px] tracking-[0.06em] text-[var(--accent-deep-purple)] whitespace-nowrap">
            {c.name}
          </span>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-text-ghost)]" aria-hidden="true">—</span>
          <span class="flex-1 min-w-[16rem] text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed">{c.text}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose">
      Evidence-sensitivity carries the argument. Without it, "the alternative is still active" cannot
      be told apart from a representation that is merely stuck. The design follows from the same
      logic: hold the available information constant and vary only the linguistic framing, so that a
      modal is compared against expressed ignorance, an explicit disjunction, and a neutral
      description — with comprehension of the expression measured, not assumed.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ THE TWO QUESTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="mt-11">
    <p class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Two questions, one account
    </p>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-medium tracking-tight mb-3">Where the evidence would come from</h2>
    <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 mb-4">
      {questions.map((q) => (
        <div class="rounded-[10px] border border-[var(--color-border)] p-4">
          <p class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.13em] text-[var(--color-text-dim)] mb-2">
            {q.label}
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text)] leading-relaxed mb-2">{q.text}</p>
          <p class="font-mono text-[10.5px] text-[var(--accent-deep-purple)] m-0">{q.term}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose">
      <span class="font-medium text-[var(--color-text)]">Status, honestly.</span> The developmental
      side is <strong>being scoped</strong> — against the existing literature, and as a question, not
      a running experiment. The computational side has an exploratory pilot, below. Neither is a
      result yet, and the evidence from either goes back to the linguistic account rather than to a
      comparison between minds and models.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ EXISTING WORK ============ -->
  <section class="mt-11">
    <p class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Methods &amp; existing work
    </p>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-medium tracking-tight mb-4">What is built</h2>

    {modus && (
      <a href={modus.href} class="block py-5 group hover:bg-[var(--color-surface)] -mx-3 px-3 rounded-md transition-colors border-t border-[var(--color-border)]">
        <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline gap-3 mb-1">
          <h3 class="text-base font-medium group-hover:text-[var(--color-accent)]">{modus.title}</h3>
          <span class="proj-output" style={`--pc: ${modus.color}`}>{modus.output}</span>
        </div>
        <p class="proj-subtitle">separating modal function from modal vocabulary</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed mt-1.5 max-w-prose">
          {modus.desc}
        </p>
        <div class="mt-2.5">
          <span class="proj-state">{modus.progress}</span>
        </div>
      </a>
    )}

    <div class="mt-9">
      <p class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
        Earlier &amp; methodological work
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose mb-4">
        Two collaborations that gave me the engineering this runs on — controlled evaluation,
        intervention inside a model, and the analysis to read the result. Methodological training,
        not the identity. What I did, in two lines.
      </p>
      <ul class="list-none p-0 m-0 space-y-5">
        {
          collaborations.map((c) => (
            <li>
              <p class="text-[15px] font-medium text-[var(--color-text)]">
                {c.name}<span class="font-normal text-[var(--color-text-dim)]"> · {c.org}</span>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose mt-1">{c.text}</p>
              {c.href && (
                <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
                  <a href={c.href} class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">{c.hrefLabel}</a>
                </p>
              )}
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* Natural-output pill + state line. The pill is tinted with the project accent. */
  .proj-output {
    flex: none;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 9.5px;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    white-space: nowrap;
    padding: 2px 8px;
    border-radius: 999px;
    color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--pc) 72%, var(--color-text));
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--pc) 38%, var(--color-border));
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--pc) 8%, transparent);
  }
  .proj-state {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 10px;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-text-dim);
  }
  .proj-subtitle {
    font-size: 13.5px;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text);
    opacity: 0.82;
    line-height: 1.4;
  }
</style>
